## Bringr-93j.19 — hover feedback dies after switching to click-to-stay

**Root cause:** Hover (slice highlight + app/window isolation) was driven by a single *global* `NSEvent` monitor. A global monitor only sees events routed to *other* apps. In hold-to-select the held chord keeps the app underneath active, so cursor moves land there (as drags) and the global monitor fires. In click-to-stay the trigger is released and the moves are delivered to Bringr's own overlay — a global monitor never sees those, so hover went dead the moment the wheel persisted.

**Fix** (`Bringr/RadialMenuWindow.swift`):
- Install a **local** monitor for the same hover mask alongside the global one. They're mutually exclusive per event (each event reaches exactly one app), so no double-counting; the local handler returns the event so the SwiftUI gesture/tracking still works.
- Set `acceptsMouseMovedEvents = true` on the overlay panel.
- Kept the dismiss monitor **global-only** on purpose — a local mouse-down monitor would double-handle the on-wheel click the SwiftUI gesture already owns and cancel the selection.
- Added an injectable `EventMonitorInstaller` seam (`.live` in production) so the monitor wiring is unit-testable.

**Test** (`BringrTests/RadialMenuControllerHoverTests.swift`, new): a recording installer asserts both a global **and** a local hover monitor are wired in **both** modes (the regression catcher), the local monitor passes events through, dismiss stays global-only, and dismiss removes every installed monitor.

**Gates:** build SUCCEEDED · `swiftlint lint --strict` 0 violations · **177 tests pass** (4 new) · app launches without crash. I couldn't physically perform the chord/gesture and sweep the cursor over slices in this environment, so the mode-independent behavior is covered by the wiring tests rather than a manual sweep.

Two notes:
- I had to register the new test file in `project.pbxproj` by hand — the project has no synchronized file groups, so a new file is silently uncompiled (the first full run "succeeded" while ignoring it; `-only-testing` reporting "Executed 0 tests" was the tell). Documented as a reusable pattern.
- The working tree has unrelated uncommitted changes from a prior iteration (a `WindowControl` → `LiveWindowSystem`/`FakeWindowSystem` split). I left those untouched; per the workflow, the engine handles commits.

